<h2>Skills</h2>

<h3>Agility Skills:</h3>

<div>
    <h4>Unarmed/Dodge</h4>
    <p>The Unarmed/Dodge skill is used when the character wishes to strike at an enemy without wielding a suitable melee weapon, they make an Unarmed skill check to attack.   Dodge can be used defensively against melee attacks and, for certain attacks (like from larger monsters or mechanical foes) making a Dodge check is the smartest option as parrying (see Melee) will incur major penalties. Complexity: Adds a threat range of 1 meter per complexity level; also allows for 1 attack of opportunity per complexity level.</p>
    <p>Complexity: Adds a threat range of 1 meter per complexity level; also allows for 1 attack of opportunity per complexity level.</p>
    <h5>Specializations:</h5>
    <dl>
        <dt>Brawling</dt>
        <dd>+1 to unarmed/dodge checks when unarmed.</dd>
        <dt>Skirmisher</dt>
        <dd>+1 to offensive strikes with light melee weapons when using with the Unarmed/Dodge skill to attack.</dd>
        <dt>Nimble</dt>
        <dd>+1 to defensive Unarmed/Dodge checks, regardless of loadout.</dd>
        <dt>CQC training</dt>
        <dd>Grants reactionary attacks with Unarmed/Dodge skill regardless of loadout.</dd>
    </dl>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Stealth</h4>
    <p>Stealth measures the ability to both move quietly under the shadows.  Stealth rolls are often rolled against opposed Notice checks for detection. A Stealth roll can be made while running at a -2, cannot be made while moving at a sprint.</p>
    <p>Complexity: The Stealth complexity sets the complexity for the notice check.</p>
    <h5>Specializations:</h5>
    <dl>
        <dt>Armored training</dt>
        <dd>Removes 15 lbs of armor when calculating penalties to Stealth checks.</dd>
        <dt>Assassin</dt>
        <dd>+1 to Stealth checks while approaching an enemy for a silent takedown.</dd>
        <dt>Running Shadow</dt>
        <dd>Stealth checks can be made while sprinting at a -3.</dd>
        <dt>Camouflage</dt>
        <dd>Add Creativity to Stealth check while Standing still as a Concealment bonus.</dd>
    </dl>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Small Arms</h4>
    <p> Small arms skill is used to fire hand held firearms in shootouts. Small arms can be used with Pistols, SMGs, Rifles, and Shotguns.  Smalls arms is also used with the manipulation of the firearms during combat reloading, manual reloading, and unjamming their weapon.</p>
    <p>Complexity: Measures the ability to use more complex weapons.  Weapons with higher complexity than the user will incur penalties equal to the difference.</p>
    <h5>Specializations:</h5>
    <p>Small Arms users can choose to specialize in a weapon class covered in the description of the Small Arms skill. This gives them a +1 to all Small Arms rolls with that weapon.</p>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Sleight of Hand</h4>
    <p>Sleight of Hand is the ability to manipulate hands with quick undetectable movements. Pickpocketing/stealing: A roll is made to pickpocket/ or steal without being detected.  A Sleight of Hand roll is made against notice checks, a successful MOS of 1 or more means the item has been taken without detection.  Small items can be swapped out (IE playing cards, a pen, sim cards) in front of opposing players by rolling off Sleight of Hand against notice as well. Difficulty penalties can be adjusted, here are some examples. Dim room: +1  Dark room: +2   Item in plain sight: -1    Item fastened to target: -2</p>
    <p>Complexity: The Complexity of the Sleight of Hand set’s the complexity for the opposing Notice check.</p>
    <h5>Specializations:</h5>
    <dl>
        <dt>Quick draw</dt>
        <dd>A character may draw light weapons as a free action without incurring a reactionary attack.</dd>
        <dt>Magician</dt>
        <dd>May perform simple magic tricks to distract interested parties, -1 to distracted parties’ Notice checks while performing.</dd>
        <dt>Swap Master</dt>
        <dd>+1 to swapping items, can be done as a quick action.</dd>
        <dt>Thief</dt>
        <dd>+1 to pickpocket or steal checks.</dd>
    </dl>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Exo-Pilot</h4>
    <p>The Exo-Pilot skill is representative of a character’s ability to move an Exo-Suit in the way they want during a combat or otherwise difficult situation. This is commonly reflected in dodging ranged and melee attacks, and attacking with melee weapons while piloting an Exo-Suit and is commonly affected by the Maneuver stat of the Exo-Suit being piloted.</p>
    <p>Complexity: Measures the ability to use more complex Exo-Suits.  Exo-Suits with higher complexity than the user will incur penalties equal to the difference.</p>
    <h5>Specializations:</h5>
    <dl>
        <dt>Infantry Hunter</dt>
        <dd>While shooting at smaller targets than your Exo-Suit, you take a -1 penalty to the roll, rather than a -2.</dd>
        <dt>Real Steel</dt>
        <dd>+1 to close combat Exo-Suit attack rolls against other Exo-Suits.</dd>
        <dt>Swift</dt>
        <dd>Confer +5m of movement to piloted Exo-Suits.</dd>
    </dl>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Zero G Movement</h4>
    <p>Movement checks in 0 gravity conditions must be made with appropriate skill and condition.  Zero G Movement handles the initial kick off of unassisted 0 G. When a man maneuver unit is attached, Zero G Movement is also used to calculate accuracy of the move.  Firing a firearm with any sort of recoil will also incur a Zero G movement check in order to prevent being immediately pushed back.</p>
    <p>
        Complexity: Complexity adds to the 0 G movement roll.
        <br />Example Checks are as follows:
        <br />Double 0 G speed: (DC 4),  Firing a firearm (DC 4+ROF) Dangerous obstacles: (DC set by GM)
    </p>
    <p>Specializations: Zero G Movement Specialization is simple enough to add a +1 each time a Zero G Movement specialization is taken.</p>
</div>

