<div>
    <h4>Computers</h4>
    <p>The Computer skill judges a character's ability to communicate to machines. The skill covers multiple operations that can be performed.</p>
    <p>
        Hacking: The art of accessing non authorized computers.  This function performs as an attack against an encryption defense or a Counter-Hacking roll.
        Counter-Hacking: Sometimes an Encrypted drive is not enough, A character may manually counter hack when a threat is detected, taking over the automated defense checks.
        Drone Jacking: After a WIR port is identified, a Computer check can be made to jack into drone’s.  Drones can be controlled for a short period of time directly or commanded to do a function included on their AI Command list.
        Drone Controlling: Having a knowledge in computer systems gives you the tools needed to maintain and operate drones around you.  Computers (Drone Controlling) Will allow you to bring a Drone NPC who will operate at the Drone controllers commands given that the character has some kind of drone controlling device equipped.  The strength and amount of Drones that may be brought are determined by the characters Computer skill Complexity.  The Accumulated level of AI controlled must be equal to or less than the characters Computer skill complexity. A Specialization in Drone controlling Adds 1 to the amount of cumulative AI levels that can be controlled at once.
        Software Guru: Day to day computer operations which include information Gathering, Downloading Data, operating complex systems.
    </p>
    <p>Complexity: Is based off of the computer system that is being operated.  AI chips set their own complexities, when hacking a computer, the complexity of the Encryption drive sets the CPX of the hack, unless it becomes Counter-Hacked in which the CPX is set by the highest of the encryption drives and the users CPX rating.</p>
    <p>Specializations: +1 to one of the following (Hacking, Counter-hacking, Drone Jacking,Drone-Controlling, Software Guru.)</p>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Communications</h4>
    <p>The Communications skill judges a character's ability to utilize communications equipment over various distances and through various mediums. Communications checks are most often made when a character attempts to communicate across long distances using a technological medium. The check DC is determined as follows:</p>
    <p>
        Basic Communications distance (dependant on equipment): DC 1
        Past Communications distance up to 2x:   DC 4
        DC Modifiers:  Static interference(+1-4), Urban Environment (+2), Jungle (+1), Underground (Halves base comm range, +2), Jamming (add opponent's ECM/Electronics Warfare roll to DC.)
    </p>
    <p>Calling in a strike: Certain weapons allow the use of Communications as an attack type.  (IE calling in airstrikes, laser designating locks.)  A character who wishes to call Indirect fire on a target or use a laser designator to acquire a lock for an allies weapons system may do so if that allies weapon is within range. The character calling in the strike may roll his Communications check along with the ally who is firing the weapon system.  The lower of the two rolls is used as the appropriate attack roll for that weapon system.</p>
    <p>Complexity: The Complexity of the Communications check is dependant on the Complexity of the equipment being used to communicate. If the character’s complexity in Communications is higher than that of the equipment, the difference in Complexity will be added to the Communications roll. The opposite is true if the Communications Complexity is lower than that of the equipment.</p>
    <p>Specializations: Communications Specializations can be taken for specific communication systems or media (examples include Shipboard Communications, Personnel Communications, Exo-Suit Communications, etc.); this will grant a +1 to Communications checks when the specialization is relevant.</p>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Navigation</h4>
    <p>The Navigation skill judges a character's ability to orient themselves geographically and travel unassisted over long distances. Navigation checks are most frequently made when attempting to find the character’s own location when lost, or to travel to a destination by means other than a clearly defined map or coordinate system.</p>
    <p>Complexity: The Complexity of Navigation adds to Navigation checks; additionally, there is Navigation oriented equipment that cannot be used unless the character’s Navigation Complexity is equal to or greater than the Navigation equipment.</p>
    <p>Specializations: Navigation Specializations can be taken for specific navigation systems(examples include Shipboard Navigation, Land Navigation, Stellar Navigation, etc.); this will grant a +1 to Navigation checks when the specialization is relevant.</p>
</div>

<h3>Influence Skills</h3>

<div>
    <h4>Haggling</h4>
    <p>The Haggling skill judges a character's ability to negotiate prices and gain deals in a mercantile setting. Haggling skill checks are typically rolled when purchasing or selling goods, and are typically opposed by the Haggling of the other party.</p>
    <p>Haggling Discount percentage= (Complexity*Influence)</p>
    <p>To make a Haggling check, roll opposed Haggling skill checks with target trader.  The MOS of your Haggle check is multiplied by the Discount Percentage (determined above) to determine the final discount. Note: MOF will not increase the price, but may worsen the shopkeeper’s disposition towards the Haggling character at the DMs discretion.</p>
    <p>Complexity: The Complexity of Haggling adds to the discount percentage.</p>
    <p>Specializations: Haggling Specialization is simple enough to add a +1 each time a Haggling specialization is taken.</p>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Bluff</h4>
    <p>The Bluff skill judges a character's ability to bend the truth or outright lie to other characters. Bluff skill checks are typically rolled when telling lies to a suspicious party, and are automatically opposed by the Human Perception. Additionally, a character may use Interrogation to roll an additional check against a character's Bluff. Using Interrogation in this way may worsen the target’s disposition, at the GM’s discretion. (See Interrogation)</p>
    <p>Complexity: The Complexity of Bluff sets the difficulty of the opposed check.</p>
    <h5>Specializations:</h5>
    <dl>
        <dt>Slippery</dt>
        <dd>The character gains a +1 to Bluff checks to beat opposing Human Perception checks.</dd>
        <dt>Tough Nut to Crack</dt>
        <dd>The character gains a +1 to Bluff checks to beat opposing Interrogation checks.</dd>
    </dl>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Leadership</h4>
    <p>Leadership determines a character’s ability to evaluate a combat and communicate tactical advice to their allies in the chaos of battle. On the ground, Leadership allows for bonuses to be given to allied combatants in the form of orders as detailed below. In the air, a leader may command a wing or a multi-crewed ship and use leadership and quick thinking in place of their allies’ combat sense (placing his crew in any order he sees fit during that initiative step).</p>
    <p>Complexity: Complexity is added to the Leadership roll.</p>
    <h5>Specializations:</h5>
    <dl>
        <dt>Ground movement Orders:</dt>
        <dd></dd>
        <dt>Fire on my target:</dt>
        <dd> Leadership check DC 4(+1 per person commanded). Standard action command. Mark a target within sight for priority, all shooters who accept order gain an immediate aim dice towards target, aim dice is lost at end of round.</dd>
        <dt>Break Suppression:</dt>
        <dd>Leadership check versus suppressive fire roll(+1 per person commanded). Quick action. All characters who accept order immediately pass Willpower checks from suppressive fire.</dd>
        <dt>Covering Fire:</dt>
        <dd>DC 4(+1 per person commanded). Covering fire. Quick action. All characters who accept the order and commence suppressive fire will add a +1 difficulty bonus against any enemies’ Willpower check to break suppression; additionally, all Suppressed enemies will suffer a 1 die penalty to offensive actions for every character laying suppressive fire on them until the end of the round.</dd>
        <dt>Snap out of it!:</dt>
        <dd>DC 6.  One character may be selected who is currently dazed by a failed combat sense.  This person is snapped back into the fight at the end of the combat sense order.</dd>
        <dt>Work through the pain</dt>
        <dd>DC 6. One character may remove an amount of wound penalties up to the MOS of the leadership check for one non combative skill check.</dd>
    </dl>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Interrogation</h4>
    <p>The Interrogation skill judges a character's ability to find the truth of a situation. Interrogation skill checks are preceded by specific queries, and then typically rolled in opposition to the Bluff of the other party. A successful Interrogation result would tell if the opposing character is lying or not.</p>
    <p>Forceful Interrogation: This skill, when used against an unwilling subject who refuses to disclose any information, is opposed by Willpower and a successful Interrogation check forces an answer from the subject. (This answer may also be a lie, however if so, it will directly result in a Bluff check.)</p>
    <p>Complexity: The Complexity of Interrogation is compared to the difficulty of the opposing Bluff check.</p>
    <p>Specializations: Interrogation Specialization is simple enough to add a +1 each time a Interrogation specialization is taken.</p>
</div>

<div>
    <h4>Animal Handling</h4>
    <p>The Animal Handling skill judges a character's ability to train, manipulate or otherwise order animals. Animal Handling skill checks are typically rolled when interacting with animals, and are typically opposed by the Instinct of the animal being handled.</p>
    <p>Animal Companion: when this specialization is taken, a character gains access to an animal Ally that scales with the characters animal handling level.</p>
    <p>Complexity: The Complexity of the animal handler is measured against the instinct of the animal.</p>
